{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_burt_ver03/data/sn97063183/00414187766/1945121401/0318.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nObservations\nMrs. Truman Not\nBindinpr Self by\nSocial Precedent\nHr HELEN EBSARY\nMr\u00ab. Truman certainly la doing\nah* pleases It I* a pleasure to\n\u25a0watch her knock down precedent*.\nIhsrt .larly serial precedents\nThere were thoae observer* who\nsal'! Oh dear! Mra. Truman Isn't\ngoing to hold preaa conference*.\nWhat an unexciting course for the\nFirst I-aily to take! Particularly af\nter Mrs Roosevelt\"\u2019\nA mistaken prophesy Indeed.\nMr*. Truman Is following her own\nunconventional bent with as much\npersistence as Eleanor Rooseielt\never showed. Take the matter of\nparty-giving and party going.\nMrs, Truman was guest of honor\nat a lady dinner'' g'Jven by Mra.\nJoseph E. navies, wife of the for\nmer ambassador to MoscoV. The\ndinner waa quite formal. Low cut\nevening gowns, diamond and ruby\ntrimmings here and ther not with\nin the memory of the oldest ehron\nlcler of the capital gossip has any\nFirst Lady ever gone to a formal\ndinner for pals alone.\nMrs. Truman created an even,\nmore remarkable social precedent\nearlier in the fall. She went to a\nformal luncheon at which she was\nnot the guest of honor. Previous\nfirst ladies have never gone any\nwhere \"hen they were not the\netars. This was extraordinary In\ndeed.\nMrs. James F. Byrnes, wife of the\nsecretary of slate, w'as the lunch\neon guest of honor. 1 was a shade\nembarrassed when I asked the wife\nof the President of the United\nStates \u2018\u2018to come, too.\" But Mr*.\nTruman did \"come, too.\" Likewise\nher daughter. Margaret. It was\nvery pleasant luncheon. We had\nlots of fun. and I learned much\nabout lack of affectation In high\nplaces.\n\"Just forget me.\u201d said Maude\nByrnes. \"You\u2019ll want to look after\nMrs. Truman.\u2019\u2019 \"Don't give me a\nthought,\u201d laughed Bess Truman.\n\u2022'The party la really for Mrs.\nByrnes.\"\nWhen Mrs Truman entertained\nnewepaper and radio women re\ncently at a supper, she obviously\ndecided she would not Invite the\nentire feminine press brigade to a\nsingle affair.\nMrs. Truman asked the women\nehe wanted to ask for this occae on.\nShe said she would not crowd the\nstate dining room with too many\ntable* Nor did she want guests\nstanding around, buffet style, with\nplates In their hands. She would\ngive two or three suppers. But she\nwould give them In her own way.\nStill further proof of Mrs. Tru\nman s social precedent smashing:\n6he la entertaining wives of offi\ncers of the Army and Navy and the\n\u25a0wires\u2019 husbands at several forth\ncoming teas. Mrs. Roosevelt used\nto have the ladles In solid blocs for\ntea. Bloc after bloc of ladies. Mrs.\nTruman is Inviting the gentlemen,\ntoo. She may be getting bored with\ntoo many females.\nOne more Item to proTe my prece\ndent breaking point\u2014when Mrs.\nTruman gives out the l.s*. of her so\ncial engagement* to the pres* she\ndoes not give all of the engage\nments. Here and there, If you keep\nyour ears open, you hear of lunch\neons and teas, unpublicized. Nat\nurally she has a right to go place*\n\u25a0without heralding, if she did no*,\nhave the right she would do it\nanyhow. So that's that.\nStill another word. Mrs. Truman\nwent to her husband's news con\nference recently. Sat right out front\nwhere she could fix a discerning\neye on some of the press. I'll bet\nshe was sizing up the crowd. And\nthat later on she said something\nlike this:\n\"I liked the look* of that young\nman in the front row, third from\nyour desk on the left. But the one\nfarther over near the window ap\npeared to be picking a fuas. Most of\nyour answers to the question* were\ngood. But 1 thought, Harry, you\nmight have been a little sharper\nwith the one about..\nWhat an entertaining family, the\nTrumans! With showmanship quite\nof their own variety. The way Mr\nTruman Jumps up In the air and\nsails away to see his mother on\nher birthday\u2014without tell.ng any\none but the aiprlane pilot. Some\nday. somebody Is likely to say:\n\u2018Haven't seen Harry around town\nlately Where has he been?\"\n\u2022Shucks, didn't you know? He\ntook It into his head to have a per\neonal talk with Chiang Kai-Shek.\nSo he hopped off to Chungking day\nbefore yesterday. Sure he Is back.\nCot n today lie s down at the old\nsw mming hole In the White House\nthis \\erv minute. Talking things\nover with the boys.\"\nTEN ENROLL IN\nFRYBLRG SCHOOL\nLondon. Mich.\u2014Becent new pu\npils at Fryburg School include\nChari* s. Mary Agn*-6s, Helen. Nei\nta and Robert I>e Yee; Carl. Tho\nmas and Gerald Hell. Betty and\nDaniel Bamier, and Thomas Alton.\nThe enrollment now is 2.1.\nThe older children will particl\npate in th** county spelling con\ntests.\nHall Forgotten Days\nTwenty Years Ago\nN't offi- err for the ensuing year were elected nl th** meeting of\nthe Woman's Benefit Association. Miss I.eora Binder command*-\u25a0:\nMrs I. M Tetters, lleut.-commander; Mrs. Edna Clough, pant\nCommander: Mrs Thereat Welch, record keeper; Mrr Elizabeth\nJohnson, ihapialn; Mrs. Marie Riley, lady at-arms; Mi Alma\nClough, sergeant: Mrs R!* key Block, sentinel Mr- Sarah Goarst,\npit k\u00bb*t, Mlis Neoma Block, musician.\nFifty Years A^o\nTr gresslve Lodge number five. Ord* r of the Red ('roar, elected\nthe following Officers for the ensuing y.-ar y a Martin, com\nmander; Mrs. Josephine Osgood, prela't Mr*. I K. Bell, secre\ntary, J Couch, flnaaie keeper; M. B Schaffer, tieasurer;\nThomas Creech, past commander.\n\nProfessor Daniel Putnam addressed the Student.-*' rhristlan As\nsociation in Newberry Hall, Ann Arbor,\nYour Health\nStreptococcus May\nFollow Other Nose,\nThroat Infections\nBy HERMAN BUNDESEN. M. D\nA COI.D Is sn infection of ths\nnose and throat. At present, the\nmost prevalent idea is that colds\nare originally due to a virus, that\nis, an organism so small that it can\npass through a porcelain filter.\nHowever, infection with germs\nsuch as streptococcus and staphyl\noeoccue easily follows the virus\ninfection.\nThe same tort of thing may also\noccur in a disorder known as acute\nlaryngotracheobronchitis accord\ning to Doctor Harry L. Baum of\nDenver, Colorado. Doctor Baum\nthinks that this condition is also\nprimarily a virus infection which\nis followed by infection of tha\ntiasuea by streptococcus germs\nFever And Cough\nIn aryngoiricheobronenuia,\nthere are fever, cough and diffi\nculty in breathing, since the dis\norder causes swelling of the lin\ning membrane of the voice box or\nlarynx and the trachea or wind\npipe, as well as the small tubes m\nthe lungs known as the bronchi.\nIt was believed for some time that\nthe condition was due primarily\nto streptococcic infection. Hence,\nit was hoped that the sulfonamide\ndrugs, which are active against\nsuch infections, might be helpful\nin the treatment of the condition.\nAccording to Doctor Baum, the\nsulfonamide drugs have proven of\nlittle value. Furthermore, penicil\nlin also, he thinks, will not be help\nful in treating the primary infec\ntion, but may be useful in combat\ning the atrcptococcua infection\nwhich follows.\nIt is suggested that perhaps the\nbest method of treatment available\nat present for lary ngotracheobron\nchitia is the use of Wood serum\ntaken from a person who has re\ncently recovered from an attack of\nthe disorder. It is frequently found\nthat some member of the patient's\nfamily has recently recovered from\nabout the same type of respiratory\ninfection aa that from which the\npatient with laryngotracheobron\nehiti* is suffering. If such serum is\nnot available, Doctor Baum thinks\nantistreptococcic serum or scarlet\nfever serum may be administered.\nThe amount of serum to be given\nwill depend upon the severity of\nthe infection and the site of the\npatient. Little improvement is to\nbe expected during the first 24\nhours, but after that time the\nsymptoms steadily disappear.\nSometimes the condition is so se\nvere as almost completely to shut\noff the breathing passages.\nIn some instances, this may be\nrelieved by using an instrument\nknown as a laryngoscope through\nwhich the accumulated secretions\nmay be sucked out. In some severe\ninstances, it may be necessary to\ndo an operation known aa trache\notomy in which an opening into\nthe windpipe is made from the out\naide.\nI aryngotracheobronchitis la a\nserious disorder which requires\nprompt treatment.\nTHEY SA Y\nLondon Sir John Anderson,\nchancellor of the exchequer in the\nChurchill government discusses\nthe projected American loan to Bri\ntain: \"We're had to accept a very\nIhud bargain, and the theory held\nin America that when an American\nandfl\u00dfriton get together the Ameri\ncan is outsmarted, has been shown\nto be entirety baseless\n\nWashington\u2014Dr. Alvin M. Wein\nberg. atomic scientist: \"The Navy\nof the future, if there la any such\nthing, will consist of submarines\nwhich will travel a thousand feet\nunder the ocean\n\nWashington\u2014Col. Bernard Bern\nstein, Army's chief cartel investiga\ntor: \"German industry merely ts\nnot functioning now. It Is tem\nporarily out of action for lack of\nmaterials. If German Industry Is\nput back in operation it would pro\nduce war materials at the end of\nfive or ten years.\"\n\nWashington\u2014John Snyder, dlrec\ntor of the Office of War Mobiliza\ntion and reconversion: \"Immediate\ndemand for new housing is far in\nexress of our capacity to produce\nnext year. Asa result the threat\nof inflation is greater in this Held\nthan In any other.\"\nAnn Arbor Given\nNew School Site\nAnn Arbor, Dec. 14 \u2014The city has\nbeen given eight acres of land be\ntween W Liberty St and Pauline\nDlvd by the University. to be\nused as a site for anew elementary\nschool.\nA west side school to replace\nBach School will he built. Funds\nfor construitlon are being placed\nIn a sinking fund made possible by\nan increase in city taxes last year.\nWorkers Want Jobs\nNot Idleness Pay\nBy HA! h 1 ACE\nTwo men who have been life-long\nfriends will have occasion to re\nmember the month of August. IMS.\nfor a long time to come. Sgt. Peter\nPugh, waiting for invasion on an air\ncraft carrier off the coast of Japan,\nheard that the war was over Hank\nHsines, welder In e medium bomb\ner plant, drew with hia pay envelop*\na notice that hia job had come to\nan end became medium bombers\nwere no longer needed.\nOs course the sergeant was not\ndischarged immediately. Neither\nwas Hank\u2014not Immediately. He had\ntwo weeks. Then he went downtown\nto file his unemployment compensa\ntion claim and put in an applica\ntion with the United State* Em\nployment Service for anew Job.\nWithin elx weeks he was back at\nthe aircraft factory, but Instead of\nwelding part* for medium bomber*\nhe was working on the engine of a\ngiant passenger plane.\nThen Peter came home. Before he\nwent off to the Pacific he had\nworked at the same plant, did the\nvery seme type of work Haines was\nnow doing. Peter needed a Job and\nsince he was a veteran. Haines once\nmore had to give up his position and\nfile another claim with the unem\nployment compensation office.\nFiction? The names are. But the\nstories contain facts that have been\nhappening thousands of times In all\nparts of the country since the war\nended. Facts like these are telling\nsome Important thing! to an agtncy\nin Washington that was set up at\nthe bottom of the depression to try\nto help people meet the economic\ncrisis that comes to almost every\none some time. This agency Is tha\nSocial Security board, and I am\nthinking particularly of that dlvli'on\nof it which administers the state un\nemployment compensation laws.\nThe sudden end of the war brought\nmanifold problems to this agency.\nLike many others, it had expect\ned reconversion and demobilisation\nto be gradual procesaei and unem\nployment aid was ready to meet that\nTowards Zero\nSYNOPSIS\nla WrSraary a laaa tiara nl ililttac\na raralalljr d.tailr* pr.jwct tar atartar.\nIha writer Irarad a data ta liapttaNr,\nthra baraed the paprr ta aakra. Fel\nlowtag are the ctrcamalaarra tkal\nbrought rertaia people\u2014 laeladtag that\nlone Agare\u2014ta Galra Fatal, trae ml\nelderly l ady Camilla Treaaillaa. aa that\nfateful date. Haadaoam Nerlia straage.\n.mill.. keir. aad Kay. kla plaaaare\nlortng bride, were ta bare aera\namilla'a gaeata la Uaae. bat Kay dis\nliked glrlag ap a yaektlag party aebed\nalrd far that Uaae\u2014 \"jaat la be saabbed\nby year prim rrlatlraa.\" Camilla, aad\nMary Aldla, a dlataat retailer wbe\nleaked after tha laealld matrtarrh. Salt\nthat Neylle bad treeled kla Seat wife.\nAadrey, meat ahamafally, wkea, ajjaf\neight yeare af happiaeee. ba bad laltea\nbepetaealy la lore with the glamereaa\nKay. Aadrey. ml wham \u00bbb\u00abr weaa rary\nfaad. bad audrred a aarreaa brsakdawa\nfnttewlag tha and I Terra Sba la Saba a*\namilla'a la September, aad Kay la\neetoaaded wbea Keelle raggeela they\npeetpone their rialt till Ihra. adding,\nII woald make ate aaet bePt**ar II\nfoa two roald ba trleada. Hr wrHrt\namllla ta this e\u00abae\u00ab. bat ahe deeidee\nta ranaalt Aadrey before yaetdlag M\nbis prepaateroaa arapaeal.\nMark fa (amilla'a aerpefae. Aadrey\napproves the Idea.\nla May, Thomaa Keyda laaeaa bla\nMalayan plaatatlea far a dab ta Kag\nland \u2014hia Aral la aaaea years. Three\ntears before kla brother Adrian had\nren killed la a motoring nreidrat ami\nAadrey. kla beleead eeaata. bad di\nre reed Wet He strange. la Jaaa. aid Mr.\nTrarrs. tka famed ertmlaelaglst. aa\ngagea rooms tor September at Maaral\nlorrt, an laa near Gall's Talat.\nKay rente mpi a tee her ylalt to OamK\nla'a with Ira# misgl rtag wkea Tad\nI.ntlmer. a farmer nailer, dlaeloaaa be\nwill be at tka Keelerhead Hotel, directly\naeroos tho bay from Gall's Talat. Se-\nCerlateadeat Kaffir, af Seatlaad Tard.\nrads far Ibat elrlalty also. U opted a\nfew days with kla caaata, dim Laart,\nloeal police laapeetor\nWbea Thomas Royde arrlred at Gall a\nToiat ta September, be aeaeed Ike at\nmosphere af tea plea smear Camille's\n111 assorted gaeata Kay made aa rPert\nto eon real her dislike *f Aadrey. aad.\ntheagh tka latter seemed her aaaal\nrheratlag aelf. Thomas glimpsed a leak\naf analogy ta her eyes.\nCHAPTER ELEVEN\nTHERE WAS change in Aud\nrey Strange, Thomaa decided. She\nwad thinner, paler, altogether more\nethereal looking\u2014but there wax\nsomething elae, something he\ncould not quite define. It was as\nthough \u00bbhe were holding herself\ntightly In leash, watchful over\nevery movement\u2014and yet all the\ntime Intensely aware of every\nthing going on round her. She wre\u00bb\nlike a person, he thought, who had\na secret to hide. But what secret?\nHe knew a little of the events that\nhad befallen her In the last few\nyears He had been prepared for\nlines of sorrow and lota\u2014but this\nwas something cite. 8h\u00bb was like\na child who, by a tightly clenched\nhand over a treasure, calls atten\ntion to what it wants to hide.\nAnd then hia eyes went to the\nother woman\u2014 the girl who was\nnow Nevile Strange's wife Beau\ntiful, yes. Mary Aldin had been\nright He rather fancied danger\nous, too. He thought: 1 wouldn't\nlike to trust her near Audrey If\n\u2022he had a knife In her hand.\nAnd yet why should she hate\nNevile's first wife? All that was\nover and done with. Audrey had\nno part or parcel In their Uvea\nnowadays\nFootsteps rang out on the ter\nrace, as Nevile came round the\ncomer of the house. He looked\nwarm and was carrying a picture\npaper.\n\"Here\u2019s the Illustrated Review,\"\nhe said. \u201cCouldn't get the other\u2014\"\nThen two thlnge happened at\nprecisely the same minute.\nKay said: \"Oh, good, give it to\nme,\u201d and Audrey, without moving\nher head, held out her hand al\nmost absent-mindedly.\nNevile had stopped half way be\ntween the two women. A dawn of\nembarrassment showed In hia face.\nBefore he could speak, Kay said,\nher voice rising with a alight note\nof hysteria:\n\"I want It Give It me! Give it\nme. Nevile!\"\nAudrey Strange started, turned\nher head, withdrew her hand and\nmurmured with Just tha slightest\nair of confusion:\n\"Oh, sorry l thought you wars\nS\u00a3eaku\u00a3 (si Nsviia.\u201d\nTHE YRfiILANTI DAILY PRESS, YPSILANTI, MICH., FRIDAY. DECEMBER 14. I#4S\nsituation. But the atomic bomb\nchanged the picture and suddenly\nmillions of men end women were\nthrown onto the labor market There\nwaa a sudden rise In claims for un\nemployment Insurance the coun\ntry grappled with the problem of\ncreating Jobs for the workers who\nwere no longer needed when war\ncontracts were terminated and for\nthe boys who were doffing uniforms\nfor mufli.\nFact* on\nJoblooo Pay\nIn this first experience of Its kind\nsince the SSB came Into being some\nImportant facta are being uncov\nered\u2014answers to such questions as:\nWhs* Is the truth about peace\ninduced unemployment In this coun\ntry?\nWhen on tha average will the un\nemployment compensation periods\nrun out and the crisis become acute\nif ther* ar* not enough Jobs?\nWhat kind of people are asking\nfor Jobless pay? Is It true that {hey\nare taking this money and not both\nering to. look for work?\nLet us see what answers the Em\nployment Bureau of the. Social Se\ncurity Board Is finding to these ques\ntions as experts here In Washington\nand In the field sift through a great\nmass of data. First, I might say\nthat unemployment compensation\nclaim* at this writing are a good\nbarometer of the unemployment\nthroughout the country brought on\nby the war. Later this would not\nbe the case. When ther* is a long\nperiod of heavy unemployment, peo\nple who have been out of work for\nfour months or more would not ap\npear on the clalma lists and there\nfore would not figure in the statis\ntics. But the situation is different\ntoday. The rise In unemployment\ni* fresh and the periods of payment\nhave not yet been used up by many\nclaimant*. So the rolls reflect a\ntrue picture of the situation.\nAa thee* lines are written, the sec\nend wave *f unemploy raent te hit\nThomas Royde saw the color\ncorns up brick red in Nevile\nStrange's neck. He took three\nquick stepa forward and held out\nthe picture paper to Audrey.\nShe said, hesitating, her air of\nembarrassment growing:\n\"Oh. but\u2014\u201d\nKay pushed back her chair wlfh\na rough movement She stood up,\nthen, turning, she made for the\ndrawing room window. Royde had\nno time to move before she had\ncharged Into him blindly.\nThe shock made her recoil; she\nlooked at him as he apologized.\nHe saw thens hy she had not seen\nhim, her eyes were brimming with\ntears\u2014tsars, he fancied, of anger.\n\"Hullo,\" she said. \"Who are you\nOh! of course, the man from Ma\nlay.\"\n\u201cTea.\" said Thomaa. \u201cI'm the\nman from Malay.\"\n\"I wish to Heavsn I was in Ma\nlay,\" said Kay. \"Anywhere but\nhers! I loathe this beastly lousy\nhouse! I loathe everyone In It!\"\nEmotional scenes always\nalarmed Thomaa He regarded Kay\nwarily and murmured nervously:\n\"Ah-hum.\"\n\u201cUnless they're careful,\" said\nKay, \u201cI ahail kill someone! Either\nNevile or that whey-faced cat out\nthere!\"\nShe brushed past him and went\nout of the room banging the door\nThomas Royde stood stock still.\nHe was not quits sure what to do\nnext, but he was glad that young\nMrs. Strange had gone. He stood\nand looked at the door that she\nhad slammed so vigorously. Some\nthing of a tiger cat, the new Mrs\nStrange.\nThe window was darkened as\nNevile Strange paused in the space\nbetween the French doors He was\nbreathing rather fast.\nHe greeted Thomas vaguely.\n\"Oh \u2014er hullo, Royde, didn't\nknow you'd arrived. I say, have\nyou seen my wife?\"\n\"She passed through about a\nminute ago,\" said the other.\nNevils in hia turn went out\nthrough the drawing room door.\nHe was looking annoyed.\nThomas Royde went slowly\nthrough the open window He was\nnot a heavy walker. Not until he\nwas a couple of yards away, did\nAudrey turn her head.\nThen he saw those wide apart\neyes open, saw her lips part. She\nslipped down from the wall and\ncams towards him, hands out\nstretched\n\"Oh, Thomas.\" she said \u201cDear\nThomas! How glad I am you've\ncome.\u201d\nAs he took the two small white\nhands In his and bent down to\nher, Mary Aldin In her turn ar\nrived at the French windows See\ning the two on the terrace she\nchecked herself, watched them for\na moment or two, then slowly\nturned away and went tack into\nthe house.\nUpstairs, Nevile had found Kay\nIn her bedroom. The only large\ndouble bedroom In the house was\nLady Treaalltan\u2019s. A married cou\nple were always given the two\nrooms with communicating door\nand a small bathroom beyond on\nthe west side of the house. It was\na small Isolated suits.\nNevile passed through hia own\nroom and on Into hia wife's. Kay\nhad Bung herself down on her bed\nRaising a tear-stained face, she\ncried out angrily:\n\"So you've come! About time,\ntoo!\"\n\"What is all thla fuss about?\nHave you gone quits crazy. Kay?\"\nNevile spoke quietly, but there\nwas a dint at the comer of his\nnostril that registered restrained\nanger.\n\u201cWhy did you give that Illus\ntrated Review to her and not to\nme?\"\nthe rountry since the wsr ended Is\nmounting es the first wave recedes.\nAt the present tlmr workers are\nbring discharged because they are\nbeing displaced by servicemen who\nare bring demobilised. The first\nwave was made up of those persons\nwho found themselves nut of |nhs\noctausr war industries nad to eon\nvert te peacetime operation.\nIn the first wave about aix million\nworker* found themselves out of\nwork as a result of the ending of\nwar contracts. Os these, three mil\nlion shifted to peacetime Jobs right\naway without any Interruption, two\nmillion registered U> unemployment\ncompensation offices and about one\nmillion are unaccounted for\u2014they\nmay have found other Jobs without\nregistering In the unemployment of-,\nflee.- or they might have gone on\nvacation or retired. About 1,100.000\nformer war workers of this number\nfound it necessary to draw unem\nployment compensation. Right now\nthe claim* for Jobless pay are drop\nping each week and Social Security\nofficials say that means the full Im\npact of the first wave of unemploy\nment\u2014the reconveralon wave\u2014hat\nbeen felt. The bulk of the war work\ners have been laid off. The bulk of\nthose who are going to file for bene\nfits have already done so.\nWhat's ahead, then, is the second\nwave\u2014the unemployment which will\ncome as an aftermath of demobili\nzation.\nIt Is estimated that from six\nto nine million servicemen are\ndestined to return to Industry\nIn the next 9 to 12 months. In\naddition, about two million\nworkers who have been In gov\nernment service during the war\nwill be looking tor new Jobs.\nThat means that about eight\nmillion persons will be thrown\non the labor market In this\nsecond wave which will come\nas a result of the end of the war.\nCrisis Loom*\nBy 1947\nAs nearly si can be Judged. So\ncial Security officials see a crisis by\n1947 If there are not enough Jobs.\nThat Is. they expect that unemploy\nment compensation payments will\ncarry people over Jobless periods\nuntil about 1947, by which time pay\nmentj will have been used up. Since\nthe amount of compensation and the\nUneth of time for which It is paid\n\"Really, Kay, you are a child!\nAH this fuss about a wretched lit\ntle picture paper\n\u201cYou gave it to her and not to\nme.\" repeated Kay obstinately.\n\"Well, why not? What docs it\nmatter?\"\n\u201cIt matters to me\n*1 don't know what's wrong with\nyou. You can't behave In this hys\nterical fashion when you're stay\ning in other people's houses. Don't\nyou know how to behave in pub\nlic?\"\n\u201cWhy did you give tt to Aud\nrey?\"\n\"Because she wanted It.\"\n\"So did I, and I'm your wife.\"\n\"All the more reason. In that\ncase, for giving tt to an older\nwoman anu one who, technically,\nis no relation.\"\n\u201cShe scored off me! She wanted\nto and she did. You were on her\nside!\u201d\n\"You're talking like an idiotic\njealous child. For goodness sake,\ncontrol yourself, ami try to behave\nproperly In public!\"\n\u201cLike she docs, I suppose?\"\nNevile said coldly:\n\u201cAt any rate Audrey can be\nhave like a lady. She doesn't make\nan exhibition of herself.\"\n\"She's turning you against me!\nShe hates me and she's getting her\nrevenge.\"\n\u201cLook here, Kay, will you stop\nbeing melodramatic and complete\nly foolish? I'm fed up!\u201d\n\"Then let's go away from here!\nLet's go tomorrow. I hate this\nplace!\u201d\n\"We'va only been here four\ndays.\"\n\"It s quite enough! Do let\u2019s go,\nNevile.\u201d\n\"Now look here, Kay, I\u2019ve had\nenough of this. We came here for\na fortnight and I'm going to stay\na fortnight.\"\n\"If you do,\" said Kay, \"you'll\nbe sorry. You and your Audrey!\nYou think she\u2019s wonderful!\u201d\n\u201cI don't think Audrey is won\nderful I think she's an extremely\nnice and kindly person whom I\u2019ve\ntreated very badly and who has\nbeen most generous and forgiv\ning.\"\n\"That\u2019s where you're wrong,\u201d\nsaid Kay. She got up from the\nbed. Her fury had died down. She\nspoke seriously\u2014almost soberly.\n\"Audrey hasn\u2019t forgiven you,\nNevile. Once or twice I've seen her\nlooking at you. I don\u2019t know\nwhat la going on In her mind but\nsomething is She's the kind that\ndoesn't let anyone know what\nthey're thinking\n\u201cIt's a pity,\u201d said Nevile, \"that\nthere aren't more peopls like\nthat\"\nKay's face went very white.\n\u201cDo you mean that for me?\u201d\nThere was a dangerous edge to her\nvoice.\n\"Well\u2014you haven't shown much\nreticence, have you? Every bit of\nill temper and spite that comes\ninto your mind you blurt straight\nout You make s fool of yourself\nand you make a fool of me!\"\n\"Anything more to say?\"\nHer voice was icy.\nHe said in an equally cold tone:\n\"I'm sorry If you think that was\nunfair. But It's the plain truth.\nYou've no more self-control than\na child.\"\n\"You never lose your temper, do\nyou? Always the self-controlled\ncharming mannered little pukka\nsahib! I don't believe you've got\nany feelings. You're Just a fish\u2014\na cold-blooded fish! Why don't you\nlet yourself go now and then?\nWhy don\u2019t you shout at me, swear\nat me. tell me to go to Blazes?\u201d\nNevile sighed. His shoulders\nsagged.\n\"Oh, Lord,\u201d he said.\nTuning on his heel he left tha\nroom.\nI (To Be Continued)\nare based on previous length of em\nployment and wages. It is plain that\na period of apotty employment will\naffect a worker's future benefits.\nA different type of person It ap\nplying for Jobless compensation\nthcae days than when the system\nwas set up In the days when apples\nwere being sold on street corners\nand unemployment was a major\nthreat to family aecurity.\nIn the early thirties workers\ncollected their benefits for the\nentire period of their eligibility\nand still were without Jobs. As\not this moment they are col\nlecting for an average of lour\nweeks and then getting Jobs. To\nday more women are applying\nfor unemployment compensation\nthan men. Skilled workers make\nup mure than 50 per cent of the\nclaimants; semi-skilled rank\nnext In number.\nAs unemployment comes Into the\nnational picture again and effort*\nare made to get more complete job\nless legislation out of Congress, ar\nguments are heard that people who\nare able to get unemployment com\npensation do not bother to look for\nJobs This is answered by the So\ncial Security Board on the basil of\nwhat they have been finding out\nfrom the postwar claims.\nThey point out first that little bet\nter than one In six of the persons\nwho lost their Jobs as a result of\nreconversion is receiving unem\nployment compensation payments.\nThis shows, they say. that a worker\nprefers a job any day to being paid\nfor not working. Moreover, they\npoint to the fact that over 750.000\npersons, or about 35 per cent of the\nworkers who filed claims initially\nsince V-J Day. have already left the\nrolls and taken jobs. Then there is\nthe testimony that in two represen\ntative citie* where special itudles\nwere made It was found that two\nthirds of the workers who left the\nclaim rolls took jobs before they\ndrew any benefits at all. They say\nthat other cases can be cited to\nprove the point.\nMeantime, as the second wave of\nJobless workers hits the labor mar\nket, the unemployment compensation\nagencies prepare to handle growing\nclaims for Jobless pay unless\u2014and\nuntil\u2014peacetime industry get* its\nwheels turning to provide the Jobs\nthat are needed.\nINJURIES FATAL\nLudlngton AP Rita Srhohl. 20-\nyearold cadet nurse at St. Mary's\nHospital, was fatally Injured Wed\nnesday when a car in which she\nwas riding skidded on l\u2019S 31 and\nrolled over an embank meat.\nFor friends near and\nfar, the best'pift is\nflowers. Order now to\ninsure prompt deliver.\nDURANT\u2019S\nFlower Shop\n7 W. Mich. Phone 141\nJoin Our 1946\nChristmas Savings Club Now!\nOnce again, we are offering a com- Weekly deposit* Receive in 50 weeks\nplete schedule of Christmas Savings .25 12.50\nClubs designed to give you just what .50 25.00\nyou want in preparation for Christmas 1.00 50.00\nof 1946. First payment started De- 2.00 150.00\nccmber 1, but it\u2019s not too late to join g 250 00\nnow. Come in today. 10.00 500.00\nNational Bank of Ypsilanti\nMember Federal Reserve Bank\nMember Federal Deposit Insuranc Corp.\nDORR HEADS Hl-Y\nDetroit\u2014A P\u2014Professor Harold\nM. Door of the University of Mlchi\nAUCTION SALE\nSATURDAY, DECEMBER 15, 1 O\u2019CLOCK SHARP\nIN OSBURN\u2019S AUCTION HOUSE\n949 Sweet Rd., Ypsllantl. Sweet Rd. Is located between Holmes\nand Clark Rdt., one-fourth milt East of N. Prospect St.\nElectric washer, lamps, studio couch, arm chair, rocktra, end\ntable, stands, library table, sectional bookcase, de